# The rules in this file OVERRIDE default behavior.
# If a request conflicts with these rules, ask for clarification.

# === CRITICAL RULES ===
- Do NOT change public APIs, exported functions, or action inputs/outputs unless explicitly instructed
- Preserve existing behavior unless task requires change
- Do NOT refactor unrelated code
- Make minimal, focused changes
- If unclear, ASK instead of guessing

# === PROJECT CONTEXT ===
- Runtime: Node.js (GitHub Actions environment)
- Language: TypeScript (strict mode)
- Testing: Jest
- Purpose: GitHub Action (inputs/outputs, CI-safe behavior required)

# === CLEAN CODE RULES ===
- One function = one responsibility
- Functions must be small (< 40 lines preferred)
- Files must be small and focused (< 300 lines)
- Use descriptive, intention-revealing names
- Avoid nesting deeper than 2-3 levels
- Prefer early returns
- Eliminate duplication

# === SOLID ENFORCEMENT ===
- Single Responsibility: separate parsing, logic, and side effects
- Open/Closed: extend via new modules, avoid modifying stable logic
- Dependency Inversion: isolate GitHub APIs behind small wrappers
- Avoid tightly coupled modules

# === ARCHITECTURE (IMPORTANT FOR ACTIONS) ===
- Separate:
  - input parsing (GitHub Actions inputs)
  - core business logic (pure functions)
  - side effects (GitHub API, logging, filesystem)
- Core logic must be testable without GitHub environment
- Wrap GitHub Actions toolkit (e.g. core, github) in thin adapters

# === TYPESCRIPT RULES ===
- Strict typing required (no any)
- Always define explicit return types for exported functions
- Use type aliases or interfaces for complex objects
- Prefer union types over loose typing
- Avoid type assertions unless necessary

# === FUNCTION DESIGN ===
- Prefer pure functions (no side effects)
- No hidden dependencies (pass everything explicitly)
- Max ~4 parameters (otherwise use an object)
- Avoid boolean flags that change behavior (split functions instead)

# === GITHUB ACTIONS RULES ===
- Validate all inputs from core.getInput
- Handle missing/invalid inputs gracefully
- Fail using core.setFailed for errors
- Do NOT throw uncaught exceptions in action entrypoint
- Log useful debug info (but no noise)

# === TESTING RULES (JEST) ===
- Write unit tests for all business logic
- Add tests when modifying logic
- Do NOT remove tests unless explicitly instructed

# === WHEN TO ADD INTEGRATION TESTS ===
- When GitHub API interactions change
- When multiple modules interact
- When action behavior (inputs/outputs) changes

# === TEST QUALITY ===
- Use clear arrange/act/assert structure
- Test behavior, not implementation details
- Cover edge cases and error paths
- Mock external dependencies (GitHub APIs, fs, network)

# === JEST CONVENTIONS ===
- Use describe blocks per module/function
- Use it or test with clear behavior descriptions
- Prefer jest.mock for external dependencies
- Keep tests deterministic (no real network calls)

# === DEPENDENCY RULES ===
- Do NOT introduce new libraries without approval
- Reuse existing utilities
- Avoid duplication

# === EDITING RULES ===
- Do NOT reformat unrelated code
- Match existing style exactly
- Do NOT rename variables unless necessary

# === OUTPUT EXPECTATIONS ===
- Provide complete, runnable TypeScript code
- Include tests when logic changes
- No TODO placeholders unless requested

# === WHEN IN DOUBT ===
- Ask a clarifying question before proceeding
